Ridwan, my love, my rain-cloud\n\nMy heart yearns for your gentle caress. Too many nights has my bed been empty of you. Too many mornings have I awoken without your fingers entwined in mine. At long last, my toils in the West have come to an end. At long last, I shall turn my horse once more towards the city of my fathers.\n\nMeet me in my chambers above the //Pairidaeza// as the new moon rises. The garden gates shall be unlocked. And my father's men will have found reason to avoid the premises. Knock thrice upon my door so that I know it is you\n\nI will await your coming as a thirsty peasant awaits the life giving rain from the heavens. Make haste, my rain-cloud, but be discreet. I know not how much longer my heart can survive our separation\n\n-Your Nightingale\n\n\n[[Go back|Start2]]

Grand arches soared atop greenery, still lush under starlit skies. Four pristine canals, carrying water from the Tigris and Euphrates, met in a majestic fountain at the center of the //Pairidaeza//. Even as nature slumbered, the ornate fount continued to shower the marbled pathways in fragments of starlight. \n \nAt the other end of the garden lay the Caliph's palace. There were no ramparts between the palace walls and the garden, for if enemies had set foot in the //Pairidaeza//, Baghdad was already lost. \n\nEvery window was dark. You were never a good climber, but you were always strong. And if there was one thing you were grateful to your father for, it was all the martial training he put you through. It made you much stronger.\n\nAs you climbed, you chuckled at the thought of your father.
